        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We use the maximum bandwidth (2\,Ghz, 1.875\,Ghz usable) in continuum mode in order to reach the maximum sensitivity in the minimum amount of observing time. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The frequency are set up to match exactly our cycle 0 data at short baselines.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_NON_STD_CONT_FREQ</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To characterise in detail the spatial distribution of millimeter grains (responsible for most of the 2.6 mm emission), we need to sample baselines ranging from 100 to 1500 klambda, in order to  detect where the minimum in the visibility curve is located. Only ALMA can provide these observations and one configuration C36-7 will allow us to sample all the required baselines. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In cycle 0 we measured the flux of TW~Hydrae to
be of 70 mJy at 2.6 mm. To accurately compare the
visibility curves between wavelengths, we need a sensitivity
at least equivalent to the 870\,$\,\mu$m data of Andrews et al: rms noise
level of 2 mJy/beam for a total flux of 1.34 Jy. The same
signal-to-noise translated to
2.6 mm leads to a minimum rms noise of 0.1 mJy/beam is
required. Such an sensitivity is reached by ALMA in 1\,min on source,
but it results in an inefficient use of the array due to an
overhead/calibration time of 10\,min.
For little extra total time, we instead aim to
improve previous detections by a factor 3 and ask for 1sigma rms noise
of 0.03 mJy/beam}. This will allow us to get a very robust measurement of
the visibilities, independently of the exact shape of the visibility
curve.
 This sensitivity provides a good balance between
on source time and overhead/calibration time.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
