        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To characterise in detail the spatial distribution of intermediate size grains (responsible for most of the 450 microns emission), we need to sample baselines ranging from 20 to 700klambda, in order to sample both the large scale emission (to determine if grains are present in the outer disk) and detect whether a minimum in the visibility curve is also present at 450 microns.
Only ALMA can provide these observations and a combination of cycle 3 configurations C36-2 with the ACA array will allow us to sample all the required baselines.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Interpolating data at 870microns, 1.1 and 2.6 mm, we estimate the flux of TW Hydrae to
be of the order of 1.8 Jy at 450microns. To accurately compare the
visibility curves between wavelengths, we need a sensitivity
at least equivalent to the 870microns data of Andrews et al: rms noise
level of 2 mJy/beam for a total flux of 1.34 Jy. The same
signal-to-noise translated to
450 micronsleads to a minimum rms noise of 2.5 mJy/beam is
required. Such an sensitivity is reached by ALMA in 1\,min on source,
but it results in an inefficient use of the array due to an
overhead/calibration time
For little extra total time, we instead aim to
improve previous detections by a factor 4 and ask for 1sigma rms noise
of 0.6 mJy/beam}. This will allow us to get a very robust measurement of
the visibilities, independently of the exact shape of the visibility
curve.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
