    <prp:abstract>We propose 2 simple observations of the well-known TW Hydrae disc to bring a definite answer on the variation of grain sizes as a function of radius within its disc. These observations take advantage of 2 new capabilities offered by ALMA in cycle 3 (long baselines and high frequencies) to go one step further in our understanding of dust evolution in discs.

Comparison of SMA (870micron), ATCA (7mm) and eVLA (9mm) observations strongly suggests that the larger dust grains (&gt; cm) are concentrated in the inner parts of the disk. ALMA offers a unique opportunity to characterise the details of the mechanisms at play: grain growth and radial migration. We propose to map the continuum emission in Band 3 (2.6mm) and Band 9 (450microns)
to build a complete data set probing the disc at all spatial scales over a factor 20 in wavelength.

With about 2 hours of total observation time, we will map accurately the spatial distribution of sub-millimetre and millimetre grains, providing the first quantitative constraints on dust growth and kinematics in protoplanetary discs. These results are expected to provide very significant quantitative constraints on the dust evolution models in disks.</prp:abstract>
